AI Solution Verification Challenge
Buggy Sorting Function — JavaScript MergeSort

1. Original Buggy Code
Selected scenario: A sorting function with a subtle bug — JavaScript MergeSort implementation.

function mergeSort(arr) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) return arr;
  const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
  const left = mergeSort(arr.slice(0, mid));
  const right = mergeSort(arr.slice(mid));
  return merge(left, right);
}

function merge(left, right) {
  let result = [];
  let i = 0;
  let j = 0;
  while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
    if (left[i] < right[j]) {
      result.push(left[i]);
      i++;
    } else {
      result.push(right[j]);
      j++;
    }
  }
  // Bug: Only one of these loops will execute
  while (i < left.length) {
    result.push(left[i]);
    j++; // Bug: incrementing j instead of i
  }
  while (j < right.length) {
    result.push(right[j]);
    j++;
  }
  return result;
}

2. My Initial Observations (Before AI Analysis)
These are my honest first impressions before any AI explanation — including the ones that were incorrect.

Q1: What goes wrong when j++ runs instead of i++?
My answer: The code does not run
PARTIALLY CORRECT — the code does run but gets stuck in an infinite loop. When j increments instead of i, the loop never moves forward through the left array. It keeps pushing the same element forever.

Q2: Does JavaScript vs Python change how you read the code?
My answer: Yes
CORRECT — JavaScript uses different syntax: function keyword, let declarations, and arr.push() instead of append(). However the logic concepts are identical — loops, arrays, and index pointers work the same way.

Q3: What should the merge() function do?
My answer: Compile
NOT QUITE — merge() does not compile anything. It combines two already-sorted arrays into one sorted array. Like taking two sorted piles of cards and interleaving them into one perfectly sorted pile.

3. The Bug — Step by Step
What the Bug Is
The entire bug is one character: j++ should be i++ in the left remainder loop. This one character causes an infinite loop.

Exact Chain of Events With the Bug
left = [3, 5]
right = [1, 4]

After main while loop:
  result = [1, 3, 4]
  i = 1  (pointing at left[1] = 5)
  j = 2  (past end of right array)

Remainder loop: i < left.length → 1 < 2 → TRUE, enters loop
  push left[1] = 5 into result ✅
  j++ → j becomes 3 (WRONG — j is not used here!)
  i stays at 1 forever → loop condition still true → INFINITE LOOP 💥

The Fix — One Character Change
// BUGGY
while (i < left.length) {
    result.push(left[i]);
    j++;  // increments wrong pointer
}

// FIXED
while (i < left.length) {
    result.push(left[i]);
    i++;  // now correctly moves through left array
}

