5. Prompt 2 — Learning Through Alternative Approaches
Prompt used: Explore alternative approaches, compare pros and cons, understand trade-offs and when to use each.

My Understanding of the Fixed Solution
•	How it works: Splits array in half recursively, then merges sorted halves back together
•	Pros: Simple one-character fix, preserves the algorithm structure
•	Cons: Still uses recursion which can cause stack overflow on very large arrays
•	My alternative idea: Use JavaScript built-in sort instead

Three Approaches Compared
Approach 1 — Fixed MergeSort (Our Solution)
while (i < left.length) {
    result.push(left[i]);
    i++;  // fixed
}
•	Performance: O(n log n) — consistent
•	Readability: Medium — requires understanding recursion
•	Best for: Learning algorithms, stable sorting needed

Approach 2 — JavaScript Built-in Sort
function sortArray(arr) {
    return [...arr].sort((a, b) => a - b);
}
•	Performance: O(n log n) — browser optimised
•	Readability: Excellent — one line!
•	Best for: Most everyday production use cases

Approach 3 — Iterative MergeSort (No Recursion)
function mergeSortIterative(arr) {
    let size = 1;
    while (size < arr.length) {
        for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i += size * 2) {
            const left = arr.slice(i, i + size);
            const right = arr.slice(i + size, i + size * 2);
            arr.splice(i, left.length + right.length, ...merge(left, right));
        }
        size *= 2;
    }
    return arr;
}
•	Performance: O(n log n) — avoids recursion stack
•	Readability: Hardest to read
•	Best for: Very large arrays where stack overflow is a risk

Comparison Table
Approach	Speed	Readability	Use When
Fixed MergeSort	O(n log n)	Medium	Learning algorithms
Built-in sort	O(n log n)	Best	Production code
Iterative merge	O(n log n)	Hardest	Huge arrays

6. Prompt 3 — Developing a Critical Eye
Prompt used: Critically assess the solution, identify weaknesses, examine assumptions, evaluate maintainability.

My Initial Assessment
•	Strengths I saw: Simple fix, preserves algorithm structure
•	Concerns I had: What about equal elements?
•	Questions I had: Does it handle empty arrays? Does it work with strings?

Weaknesses Identified Through Critical Review
Weakness 1 — Equal Elements Behaviour
if (left[i] < right[j]) {  // strict less than
When elements are equal, the code always picks from right first. This makes the sort not fully stable — equal elements from left do not maintain their original order relative to right.

Weakness 2 — Only Reliable With Numbers
mergeSort(['banana', 'apple', 'cherry'])  // works alphabetically
mergeSort([10, 9, 100])  // WRONG if treated as strings: '10' < '9'
The < comparison works for numbers but behaves unexpectedly when numbers are accidentally treated as strings.

Weakness 3 — No Input Validation
mergeSort(null)       // crashes
mergeSort('hello')    // unexpected behaviour
mergeSort([{a: 1}])  // compares objects incorrectly
The function assumes input is always a valid array of numbers. No error handling exists for invalid input.

Assumptions the Code Makes
•	Input is always an array — never null, string, or object
•	All elements are numbers — no strings or mixed types
•	Memory is sufficient for recursive call stack
•	Array size is manageable — very large arrays risk stack overflow

Maintainability Assessment
Scenario	Impact
Requirements change to sort objects	Major rewrite needed
Another developer reads it	Requires recursion knowledge
Array grows to 1 million items	Risk of stack overflow
Need to sort in descending order	Requires modifying comparison logic

7. Final Verified Solution
This is the improved version incorporating all three verification strategies — fixed bug, input validation, and flexible comparison.

function mergeSort(arr) {
    // Input validation added after critical review
    if (!Array.isArray(arr)) {
        throw new TypeError('Input must be an array');
    }
    if (arr.length <= 1) return arr;
    const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
    return merge(mergeSort(arr.slice(0, mid)), mergeSort(arr.slice(mid)));
}

function merge(left, right) {
    let result = [], i = 0, j = 0;
    while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
        // <= makes sort stable for equal elements
        result.push(left[i] <= right[j] ? left[i++] : right[j++]);
    }
    // Spread operator cleanly collects all remainders
    // Eliminates the buggy remainder while loops entirely
    return [...result, ...left.slice(i), ...right.slice(j)];
}

The spread operator on the last line eliminates the buggy remainder loops entirely — making the original bug impossible to reintroduce.

